# KYWO — Capacitive Skin Sensor + UR5 Integration

A data-collection and visualization system that coordinates a **19-cell capacitive pressure mat** (Muca skin sensor) with a **Universal Robots UR5 arm**, recording force/pressure data as the robot presses each point on the mat in a hexagonal grid pattern.

---

## System Overview

```
Muca Skin Sensor (USB/serial) ──► sensor.py ──► /tmp/kywo_sensor.json
                                      │
                              data_logger.py ──► logs/session.csv
                                      │
UR5 Robot (RTDE / Ethernet) ──► ur5_control.py ─┘
                                      │
                              visualizer_2d.py  (Pygame, subprocess)
                              sofa_scene.py     (SOFA 3D, subprocess)
```

The sensor mat has 19 usable cells arranged in a 5-row hexagonal grid (3-4-5-4-3). The UR5 presses each of those 19 points in sequence, dwelling 6 mm deep for 1.5 s, while the system logs sensor pressure, 6-axis force/torque, and TCP pose at 20 Hz.

---

## Quick Start

```bash
cd Integration

# Full system (sensor + UR5 + 2D visualizer + logging)
python3.10 main.py

# Without SOFA 3D (most common)
python3.10 main.py --no-sofa

# Sensor + logging only, no robot
python3.10 main.py --no-robot

# Demo mode (simulated sensor, no hardware needed)
python3.10 main.py --demo

# Auto-stop after N seconds
python3.10 main.py --no-sofa --duration 60

# Run analysis after session ends
python3.10 main.py --no-sofa --analyze

# Analyze a saved session (standalone)
python3.10 analyze_session.py logs/my_session.csv --save
```

---

## Hardware

| Component | Connection | Default |
|-----------|-----------|---------|
| Muca skin sensor | USB serial | `/dev/ttyUSB0` (auto-detect) |
| UR5 robot | Ethernet RTDE | `177.22.22.2` |
| F/T sensor | UR5 built-in | read at 125 Hz |

---

## File Reference

### `Integration/` — Main System

#### [`main.py`](Integration/main.py)
**Central orchestrator.** Parses CLI arguments, starts all subsystems (sensor, UR5, logger, visualizers), runs the 20 Hz logging loop, and shuts everything down cleanly.

**CLI flags:**

| Flag | Effect |
|------|--------|
| `--no-sofa` | Skip SOFA 3D visualization |
| `--no-viz` | Skip Pygame 2D visualizer |
| `--no-robot` | Skip UR5 trajectory |
| `--demo` | Simulated sensor, no hardware |
| `--log-only` | Sensor + logger only |
| `--sofa-only` | SOFA 3D only |
| `--viz-only` | 2D visualizer only |
| `--analyze` | Run `analyze_session.py` after session |
| `--log-prefix NAME` | Set log filename prefix (skips prompt) |
| `--duration SECS` | Auto-stop after N seconds |

**Startup sequence:**
1. Load `calib.json` offsets into `ur5_control`
2. Start sensor (wait up to 60 s for calibration)
3. Start CSV logger (asks for prefix if `--log-prefix` not set)
4. Launch subprocess visualizers (SOFA, then Pygame)
5. Start UR5 trajectory in a background thread
6. Monitor loop: print state every 2 s, exit on trajectory-done / Ctrl-C / `--duration`

---

#### [`sensor.py`](Integration/sensor.py)
**Capacitive skin sensor reader.** Opens the serial port, reads 252-cell CSV frames at ~100 Hz, extracts the 19 used cells, applies baseline calibration and gamma correction, and exposes thread-safe accessors.

**Configuration constants:**

| Name | Default | Description |
|------|---------|-------------|
| `SERIAL_PORT` | `/dev/ttyACM0` | Falls back to auto-detect |
| `SERIAL_RATE` | 115200 | Baud rate |
| `SENSITIVITY` | 8.0 | ADC counts per full-scale |
| `GAMMA` | 0.5 | Perceptual curve (< 1 = more sensitive at low values) |
| `READ_TIMEOUT` | 2.0 s | Stale-frame threshold |
| `SHARED_FILE` | `/tmp/kywo_sensor.json` | IPC file for subprocesses |

**Key functions:**

| Function | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `start()` | Launch read thread + shared-file writer |
| `get_values()` | Return list of 19 normalized floats [0.0–1.0] |
| `wait_until_ready(timeout)` | Block until baseline calibration done |
| `recalibrate()` | Reset baseline (next frame becomes new zero) |
| `read_shared()` | Read the IPC JSON — used by subprocess visualizers |
| `is_connected()` | True if a frame arrived within `READ_TIMEOUT` |

**Normalization:** `value = clamp((raw − baseline) / SENSITIVITY, 0, 1) ^ GAMMA`

The first valid frame sets the baseline. The serial loop reconnects automatically after failures (0.3 s fast / 3 s slow depending on age of last good frame).

---

#### [`ur5_control.py`](Integration/ur5_control.py)
**UR5 robot controller.** Connects via RTDE, moves to each of 19 hexagonal points, presses 6 mm, dwells 1.5 s, retracts, and repeats.

**Motion parameters:**

| Parameter | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| Travel speed | 0.05 m/s |
| Press speed | 0.01 m/s |
| Acceleration | 0.3 m/s² |
| Press depth | 6 mm |
| Dwell time | 1.5 s |

**Key functions:**

| Function | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `run_trajectory(on_press, on_release, interactive)` | Execute all 21 waypoints |
| `get_state()` | Dict with `point`, `pressing`, `done`, `ft`, `tcp` |
| `get_force()` | Latest 6-axis F/T reading |

**Calibration offsets** (loaded from `calib.json` via `load_calibration.py`) shift every point by ΔX, ΔY, ΔZ mm before motion.

**UR5_TO_SENSOR mapping** — which raw sensor cell each UR5 point activates when pressed — was verified empirically with `verify_mapping.py`.

---

#### [`data_logger.py`](Integration/data_logger.py)
**CSV session logger.** Buffers rows in memory and writes atomically (temp file + rename) to avoid corruption.

**CSV columns:** `timestamp`, `datetime`, `ur5_point`, `ur5_pressing`, `ur5_done`, `tcp_x/y/z`, `fx/y/fz`, `tx/ty/tz`, `cell_1` … `cell_19`

**Key functions:**

| Function | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `start(filepath)` | Open log file, write header |
| `log(sensor_vals, ur5_state)` | Append one row (call at 20 Hz) |
| `stop()` | Flush buffer and close file |
| `get_row_count()` | Number of rows written so far |
| `build_filename(prefix, dir)` | `{prefix}_session_{YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS}.csv` |
| `ask_file_prefix()` | Interactive prompt for prefix |
| `sanitize_name(s)` | Strip special chars from prefix |

---

#### [`visualizer_2d.py`](Integration/visualizer_2d.py)
**Pygame 2D hex pressure map.** Runs as a subprocess, reads sensor state from `/tmp/kywo_sensor.json`, and renders a live hex grid.

**Left panel:** 19 hexagonal cells colored by pressure (black → blue → green → yellow → red).  
**Right panel:** Active count, peak value, current UR5 point, robot state, per-cell bar chart.  
**Status indicator:** Live / Buffered / Reconnecting / Demo.

**Keyboard shortcuts:**

| Key | Action |
|-----|--------|
| `L` | Toggle cell labels |
| `V` | Toggle numeric values |
| `C` | Recalibrate sensor |
| `D` | Toggle demo (simulated) mode |
| `ESC` | Quit |

Can also be run standalone: `python3.10 visualizer_2d.py`

---

#### [`sofa_scene.py`](Integration/sofa_scene.py)
**SOFA Framework 3D visualization.** Launched by `main.py` via `runSofa`. Renders the 19 sensor points as spheres whose height and radius grow with pressure, color-coded teal→green→yellow→orange→red.

Reads sensor data from `/tmp/kywo_sensor.json` (same IPC file as Pygame visualizer). Does not open the serial port.

**Camera shortcuts (in SOFA window):** `1` = Top, `2` = Isometric, `3` = Side.

Requires `~/sofa/SOFA_v25.12.00_Linux/` installation with the SofaPython3 plugin.

---

#### [`analyze_session.py`](Integration/analyze_session.py)
**Post-processing analysis dashboard.** Loads a session CSV and generates up to 5 Matplotlib figures.

```bash
# Analyze specific file
python3.10 analyze_session.py logs/my_session.csv

# Save figures to plots/
python3.10 analyze_session.py logs/my_session.csv --save

# Analyze all sessions + comparison table
python3.10 analyze_session.py --all --save

# Force-only analysis
python3.10 analyze_session.py logs/my_session.csv --force
```

**Figures generated:**

| Figure | Content |
|--------|---------|
| 1 — Overview | Sensor timeline + force timeline for full session |
| 2 — Per-point bars | Average peak and mean per UR5 point |
| 3 — Hex detail maps | Hex grid snapshot at each press event |
| 4 — Force analysis | Fz vs sensor scatter with linear fit and r² |
| 5 — Session comparison | Table of metrics across all sessions (`--all`) |

---

#### [`calibrate_ur5.py`](Integration/calibrate_ur5.py)
**Interactive UR5 calibration tool.** Jog the TCP in fine increments to find the exact XYZ offset that aligns each robot point with the physical sensor cell.

**Commands at the prompt:**

| Command | Effect |
|---------|--------|
| `x+ / x-` | Jog +/− along X |
| `y+ / y-` | Jog +/− along Y |
| `z+ / z-` | Jog +/− along Z |
| `step N` | Set jog step size (mm) |
| `press` | Execute a press and read sensor peak |
| `status` | Print TCP pose + sensor bar chart |
| `reset` | Return to reference pose |
| `save` | Write offsets to `calib.json` |
| `quit` | Exit without saving |

---

#### [`verify_mapping.py`](Integration/verify_mapping.py)
**Automated UR5↔sensor mapping verification.** Visits each of the 19 UR5 points, presses, reads which sensor cells activate, and prints a summary table comparing observed peaks against the expected `UR5_TO_SENSOR` mapping.

```bash
python3.10 verify_mapping.py
```

---

#### [`load_calibration.py`](Integration/load_calibration.py)
**Calibration loader.** Reads `calib.json` and patches the X/Y/Z offsets into `ur5_control` at import time. Called automatically by `main.py` on startup.

```bash
# Apply calibration manually (for testing)
python3.10 -c "import load_calibration; load_calibration.apply()"
```

---

#### [`sensor_bridge.py`](Integration/sensor_bridge.py)
**Legacy sensor interface.** An earlier version of `sensor.py` used before the shared-file IPC approach. Retained as a backup/reference. Uses the same serial protocol but exposes a `SensorBridge` class with a `recalibrate()` method and `connection_age` attribute.

---

#### [`calib.json`](Integration/calib.json)
Saved calibration offsets applied to all UR5 trajectory points.  
Format: `{"x_offset_mm": -3.0, "y_offset_mm": 1.0, "z_offset_mm": 0.0}`

---

### Root-Level Scripts

#### [`basic_routine.py`](basic_routine.py)
Cyclic Z-axis indentation test. Connects directly to the UR5 via RTDE and moves the TCP down then up repeatedly, printing force and pose at each step. Used for early hardware validation.

#### [`basic test.py`](basic%20test.py)
Linear X-axis movement test. Moves the TCP 1 cm forward then streams TCP force data continuously. Used to verify the RTDE connection and F/T sensor.

#### [`sine.py`](sine.py)
Sinusoidal X-axis trajectory. Generates a smooth sine wave motion using `servoJ` for continuous control. Demonstrates the servo interface rather than waypoint-based `moveL`.

#### [`Start.py`](Start.py)
Hello-world sanity check. Prints "Hello World!" — used to verify the Python environment is working.

---

### `RTDE_Python_Client_Library/`

Vendored copy of the Universal Robots RTDE Python client (v2.7.12).

#### [`rtde/`](RTDE_Python_Client_Library/rtde/)
Core RTDE protocol implementation: `rtde.py` (connection + send/receive), `serialize.py` (pack/unpack), `rtde_config.py` (XML recipe loader), `csv_reader.py`, `csv_writer.py`, `csv_binary_writer.py`.

#### [`hexagon_trajectory.py`](RTDE_Python_Client_Library/hexagon_trajectory.py)
Constant-Z hexagonal sweep. Visits all 19 points at a fixed height without indentation — useful for X/Y alignment checks without pressing.

#### [`indentation.py`](RTDE_Python_Client_Library/indentation.py)
Full hexagonal trajectory with per-point depth and dwell overrides. Predecessor to `Integration/ur5_control.py`, useful as a standalone script outside the integration system.

#### [`ur_position.py`](RTDE_Python_Client_Library/ur_position.py)
One-shot TCP pose reader. Connects, prints current X/Y/Z/Rx/Ry/Rz, disconnects. Handy for finding the reference pose before a session.

#### [`daq_data.py`](RTDE_Python_Client_Library/daq_data.py)
NI USB-6009 data acquisition interface via `pyusb`. Probes analog endpoints and returns raw bytes. Work-in-progress — was an early experiment for external DAQ before switching to the UR5 built-in F/T sensor.

#### [`examples/`](RTDE_Python_Client_Library/examples/)
Official RTDE example scripts: `record.py` (real-time data recording), `example_control_loop.py` (basic servo loop), `example_plotting.py` (live data plot).

